ce:section.ce:para:
To analyse the cytotoxic properties of the developed Mn-, N-CQD, the MTT assay was performed on HeLa cells and L929 cells (as healthy control) by incubating them with different concentrations (0–60 μg mL−1) of the Mn-, N-CQD for 48 h at 37 °C (Fig. 7
                        ). The Mn-, N-CQD demonstrated negligible cytotoxicity (cell viability > 90 %) up to 40 μg mL−1 in both the cell lines and beyond that, they were slightly cytotoxic with cell viabilities 79 %-83 % at 60 μg mL−1 (Fig. 7 (a) and (b)). Consequently, a concentration much lesser than 60 μg mL−1 (i.e. 20 μg mL−1) of Mn-, N-CQD was chosen and further used for developing the MTX-conjugated counterparts. Subsequently, the anti-cancer properties of the developed Mn-, N-CQD /MTX were compared to that of free drug using MTT assay by incubating both HeLa and L929 cells with free drug and Mn-, N-CQD/MTX at different drug concentrations (0–80 μM) for 24 and 48 h. As shown in Fig. 8
                         (a), the cell viability at 24 h highlighted that the activity of HeLa cells treated at the concentration of 5 μM was slightly reduced (cell viability: 75 % for Mn-, N-CQD/MTX, 78 % for free drug) demonstrating lesser cytotoxicity. The viabilities of the HeLa cells at concentrations 10, 20, 50 and 80 μM were found to be 69 %, 66 %, 61 %, and 56 %, respectively, for Mn-, N-CQD/MTX, while for free MTX, it was 71 %, 68 %, 65 % and 62 %, respectively, indicating that drug dose beyond 10 μM started showing substantial cytotoxicity. In the case of 48 h incubation (Fig. 8 (b)), the anti-cancer effect of the drug on HeLa cells began to appear significantly. The viabilities of the cells at 10, 20, 50, and 80 μM of drug dosage were reduced to 65 %, 53 %, 40 % and 21 %, respectively, for Mn-, N-CQD /MTX and to 70 %, 63 %, 49 %, and 29 %, respectively, for the free drug, signifying that the MTX-conjugated Mn-, N-CQD has substantially higher anti-cancer activity on the HeLa cells than that of a free drug due to sustained release (SR) of the drug along with better cell penetration and internalisation of the drug-delivery platform by the cancer cells. However, in the case of L929 cells, the cell viability was > 80 % at all the tested drug concentrations (at both 24 and 48 h), indicating that the ability of the drug-delivery platform does not severely affect the normal cells.

The fabricated Mn-, N-CQD and Mn-, N-CQD/MTX complex were further studied to analyse their fluorescence bioimaging potential in vitro in HeLa cells (Fig. 10
                        ). Briefly, the cells were incubated separately with both Mn-, N-CQD and Mn-, N-CQD/MTX (MTX: 50 µM) at 100 µ mL−1 concentration for 1 h, wherein a bright blue fluorescence was observed with the cell boundaries clearly visible (Fig. 10(b)) for the former, whereas for the later the obtained images had weak fluorescence intensity (Fig. 10 (d)). This also corroborates with the results of optical study, where the presence of MTX quenches the fluorescence signal. Subsequently, for further conformation, the cells were incubated with Mn-, N-CQD/MTX (MTX: 50 µM) for 24 h and 48 h under neutral (pH: 7.4) (Fig. 11
                        (a, and c)) and acidic (pH: 5.5) conditions (Fig. 11(g)). When the fluorescence images were analysed, it was discovered that the fluorescence recovery was greater under acidic conditions at 24 h (Fig. 11(e)), which increased further at 48 h (Fig. 11(g)), compared to the neutral condition. The obtained results indicate the release of MTX under acidic conditions and are consistent with the pH-dependent drug-release results observed in the solution phase.
